<div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert dark"><h3>Computation of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">-\log_2 p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.9386em; vertical-align: -0.2441em;"></span><span class="mord">−</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.1667em;"></span><span class="mop"><span class="mop">lo<span style="margin-right: 0.01389em;">g</span></span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.207em;"><span style="top: -2.4559em; margin-right: 0.05em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 2.7em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">2</span></span></span></span class="vlist-s">​</span></span><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.2441em;"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.1667em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">p</span></span></span></span> and Its Application in Huffman Encoding</h3><p>When we compute <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">-\log_2 p</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>, we obtain the minimum number of bits required to represent a set of elements with the same probability.</p><p>Let us consider a case where we have 8 objects, each with the same probability, i.e., <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-trac{1}{8}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.345em;"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mclose nulldelimiter"></span></span></span></span></span>. When we compute:</p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mn>2</mn><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">-\log_2 (2^{-3}) = 3</annotation></semantics></math></span><br></span></span><p>it implies that at least 3 bits are required if all objects have the same probability.</p><p>eneral case, we know that the average number of bits required is given by the summation:</p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mo>∑</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mtext>probability</mtext><mo>×</mo><mtext>count</mtext><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\sum (\text{probability} \times \text{count})</annotation></semantics></math></span><br></span></span><p>which, in this context, simplifies to:</p><span class="katex-display" style=""><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><semantics><mrow><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mi>log</mi><mo>⁡</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>p</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>×</mo><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">-\log_2 (p) \times p</annotation></semantics></math></span><br></span></span><p>where ass="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">p</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;represents probability and count denotes the number of occurrences.</p><p>This logic is utilized in Huffman encoding, which is why it is known to produce the least compressible form of data.</p></div>